RegionalBackbone
================

Overview
- This scenario is the first medium-scale baseline topology for the dissertation project.
- It starts with baseline validation and now includes reactive-failure, controlled-degradation, and traffic-driven congestion configs.
- It does not add predictive logic, proactive rerouting, or new C++ modules.
- Its purpose is to validate a larger OSPF topology before using it for later protective reroute experiments.

Topology
- Endpoints:
  - hostA
  - hostB
- Access routers:
  - accessA
  - accessB
- West-side aggregation/provider-edge routers:
  - west1
  - west2
- East-side aggregation/provider-edge routers:
  - east1
  - east2
- Backbone/core routers:
  - coreNW
  - coreNE
  - coreSW
  - coreSE
  - coreC1
  - coreC2

Preferred path
- hostA -> accessA -> west1 -> coreNW -> coreNE -> east1 -> accessB -> hostB

Alternative paths
- Southern corridor:
  - hostA -> accessA -> west2 -> coreSW -> coreSE -> east2 -> accessB -> hostB
- First diagonal alternative:
  - hostA -> accessA -> west1 -> coreNW -> coreC1 -> coreSE -> east2 -> accessB -> hostB
- Second diagonal alternative:
  - hostA -> accessA -> west2 -> coreSW -> coreC2 -> coreNE -> east1 -> accessB -> hostB

OSPF cost intent
- Low costs on the northern corridor make the preferred path unambiguous.
- Higher costs on the southern and diagonal alternatives keep fallback paths available without accidental ECMP in the first version.
- This makes later rerouting experiments easier to interpret because the primary and fallback path hierarchy is explicit.

Traffic
- Baseline, reactive-failure, and controlled-degradation configs use one light UDP flow from hostA to hostB.
- The traffic-driven congestion config uses one low-rate probe flow plus staged bulk UDP flows.
- Traffic starts after an initial routing-convergence period.
- Non-congestion configs keep load intentionally small so they validate routing, failure, or controlled impairment behavior only.

Configs
- `RegionalBackboneBaseline`
  - Baseline routing validation.
  - No failures.
- `RegionalBackboneReactiveFailure`
  - Pure reactive rerouting experiment.
  - Traffic starts at 20s.
  - The preferred `coreNW <-> coreNE` backbone span is physically disconnected at 40s.
  - OSPF is expected to reconverge after the failure onto an available alternative path.
- `RegionalBackboneControlledDegradation`
  - Controlled synthetic pre-failure degradation experiment.
  - Reuses the project-local `LinkDegradationController`.
  - Traffic starts at 20s.
  - The preferred `coreNW <-> coreNE` backbone span degrades from 35s to 55s using `stagedRealistic`.
  - The same span is physically disconnected at 60s.
  - OSPF is expected to react only after the hard failure.
- `RegionalBackboneCongestionDegradation`
  - Traffic-driven pre-failure congestion experiment.
  - Uses a fixed 10 Mbps bottleneck on the preferred `coreNW <-> coreNE` backbone span.
  - All other links remain at 100 Mbps.
  - Probe traffic starts at 20s.
  - Six staged bulk flows start at 35s, 50s, 65s, 80s, 95s, and 110s.
  - The same span is physically disconnected at 125s.
  - OSPF is expected to keep using the preferred path during congestion and react only after the hard failure.
- Debug variants enable eventlog recording for manual path inspection.

Congestion timeline
- 0s-20s: routing convergence, no traffic.
- 20s-35s: normal/light-load probe traffic.
- 35s-80s: rising congestion as staged bulk flows accumulate below or near the bottleneck capacity.
- 80s-125s: critical congestion as aggregate offered load exceeds the 10 Mbps bottleneck.
- 125s: physical disconnect of `coreNW <-> coreNE` by ScenarioManager.
- 125s-150s: post-failure observation and reactive rerouting.

Measurements
- Sender packet count.
- Receiver packet count.
- Receiver throughput vector.
- Receiver end-to-end delay vector.
- Receiver received sequence-number vector.
- Basic IPv4 no-route and interface-down drop counters.
- Controller-side applied delay and packet-error-rate vectors for controlled-degradation configs.
- Bottleneck queue vectors on `coreNW.eth[1].queue` for traffic-driven congestion configs:
  - queueLength
  - queueBitLength
  - queueingTime

Purpose
- Move beyond the tiny dual-path topology without jumping to an Internet-scale model.
- Provide a defensible medium topology for later baseline, reactive failure, controlled degradation, and congestion-driven experiments.
- Keep the first step small enough to debug before adding impairment or protective reroute logic.
